			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Group Leadership AAs<a name="26495"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 9 04 3:58 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>You know, my regular group is veterans of 4 years of EQ, level 65 averaging over 100 AAs.  Believe it or not, we mastered using the Assist key a LONG time ago.
<br />

<br />
I think some people need to do a better job of visualizing the situation.  You bring 3 mobs with identical names, the MA targets one and calls the attack.  At this point in time, you know ONE of those mobs is the right one, you even have it in your target window.  But which one do you click on to mez?  If you just randomly choose one of the three mobs that is running in and click, odds are 1 in 3 you will be targeted on the exact same mob you already have in your target window and the MA will break your mez as soon as it lands.
<br />

<br />
With this AA, you VISUALLY are able to tell which of the three is the MA target BEFORE they even get to melee range, can select one of the others and start mez - the druid can root or snare the adds to assist with CC, same with shaman slowing -- all without having to wait and watch the MA start hitting the target he/she has selected.  If your MA has to change targets to protect a caster that got agro, you know INSTANTLY without the MA having to announce it or without having to trial and error your way through identical mobs.
<br />

<br />
Seriously, a lot of people who HAVEN'T EVEN TRIED THIS AA are suddenly experts on it and just know my group is somehow targeting-impaired.  I beg to differ.  Having actually used this AA for a week, I can assure you that even with a very experienced, very smart, very skilled group who figured out /assist before 90% of you took up EQ, this AA is really useful.
<br />

<br />
Before you tell me what a gimp I am for finding it handy, try it and see for yourself.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
